data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, was false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use IsTrue with a message, or CollectionAssert for collection-level checks
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "All users should be active");

    // Use IsNotNull instead of Assert.IsTrue(x != null)
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` or just check exact count | Shows actual value on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Failure says "Expected 3, got 5" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer intent and message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(condition)` | `Assert.IsTrue(condition, "msg")` | Always add a message for non-obvious checks |

**Other `CollectionAssert` methods worth knowing:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);         // same order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);    // any order
```

For richer fluent assertions, consider the **FluentAssertions** NuGet package:
```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3).And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive);
```
